Think carefully through the problem of regression detection in the context of continuous deployment: how do you reliably determine that a new code deployment has caused a performance regression, given that traffic patterns vary, time-of-day effects are present, and any individual comparison window is noisy?

The fundamental challenge is the counterfactual: you cannot observe what performance would have been in the same time window without the deployment. The best you can do is compare a post-deployment window to a pre-deployment window, but these windows differ not just in code version but also in clock time, making it difficult to separate deployment effects from time-of-day effects.

Think through these comparison strategies and their failure modes:

Pre/post comparison (comparing the 30 minutes before versus 30 minutes after deployment): works well for step-change regressions but confounds the deployment with any time-correlated traffic changes. A deployment that coincides with the start of peak traffic hours will appear to cause a regression even if it is harmless.

Same-time-last-week comparison (comparing Tuesday 2pm post-deployment to Monday 2pm or last Tuesday 2pm): removes time-of-day confound but introduces week-over-week traffic growth and feature flag differences as confounds. If the service is growing, last week's baseline will have lower traffic volume.

Canary comparison (comparing a canary deployment to the stable version simultaneously): eliminates almost all confounds but requires traffic splitting infrastructure and only works when you can route a fraction of traffic to the new version. Think through the minimum canary traffic percentage and duration needed for statistically valid comparison at different traffic volumes.

Propose a decision framework for choosing among these strategies based on service traffic volume, deployment frequency, and available infrastructure, and specify the minimum detectable effect size for each strategy.
